# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mixture-of-experts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] In statistics and machine learning, **ensemble methods** use multiple learning algorithms to obtain better predictive performance than could be obtained from any of the constituent learning algorithms alone.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Unlike a statistical ensemble in statistical mechanics, which is usually infinite, a machine learning ensemble consists of only a concrete finite set of alternative models, but typically allows for much more flexible structure to exist among those alternatives.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Supervised learning algorithms search through a hypothesis space to find a suitable hypothesis that will make good predictions with a particular problem.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Even if this space contains hypotheses that are very well-suited for a particular problem, it may be very difficult to find a good one.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensembles combine multiple hypotheses to form one which should be theoretically better.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning typically refers to bagging (bootstrap aggregating), boosting or stacking/blending techniques to induce high variance among the base models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Bagging creates diversity by generating random samples from the training observations and fitting the same model to each different sample — also known as *homogeneous parallel ensembles*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Boosting follows an iterative process by sequentially training each base model on the up-weighted errors of the previous base model, producing an additive model to reduce the final model errors — also known as *sequential ensemble learning*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Stacking or blending consists of different base models, each trained independently (i.e. diverse/high variance) to be combined into the ensemble model — producing a *heterogeneous parallel ensemble*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Common applications of ensemble learning include random forests (an extension of bagging), Boosted Tree models, and Gradient Boosted Tree Models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Models in applications of stacking are generally more task-specific — such as combining clustering techniques with other parametric and/or non-parametric techniques.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Evaluating the prediction of an ensemble typically requires more computation than evaluating the prediction of a single model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] In one sense, ensemble learning may be thought of as a way to compensate for poor learning algorithms by performing a lot of extra computation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] On the other hand, the alternative is to do a lot more learning with one non-ensemble model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] An ensemble may be more efficient at improving overall accuracy for the same increase in compute, storage, or communication resources by using that increase on two or more methods, than would have been improved by increasing resource use for a single method.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Fast algorithms such as decision trees are commonly used in ensemble methods (e.g., random forests), although slower algorithms can benefit from ensemble techniques as well.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] By analogy, ensemble techniques have been used also in unsupervised learning scenarios, for example in consensus clustering or in anomaly detection.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Empirically, ensembles tend to yield better results when there is a significant diversity among the models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Many ensemble methods, therefore, seek to promote diversity among the models they combine.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Although perhaps non-intuitive, more random algorithms (like random decision trees) can be used to produce a stronger ensemble than very deliberate algorithms (like entropy-reducing decision trees).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Using a variety of strong learning algorithms, however, has been shown to be more effective than using techniques that attempt to *dumb-down* the models in order to promote diversity.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It is possible to increase diversity in the training stage of the model using correlation for regression tasks or using information measures such as cross entropy for classification tasks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Theoretically, one can justify the diversity concept because the lower bound of the error rate of an ensemble system can be decomposed into accuracy, diversity, and the other term.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning, including both regression and classification tasks, can be explained using a geometric framework.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Within this framework, the output of each individual classifier or regressor for the entire dataset can be viewed as a point in a multi-dimensional space.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The Euclidean distance is used as the metric to measure both the performance of a single classifier or regressor (the distance between its point and the ideal point) and the dissimilarity between two classifiers or regressors (the distance between their respective points).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] This perspective transforms ensemble learning into a deterministic problem.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] For example, within this geometric framework, it can be proved that the averaging of the outputs (scores) of all base classifiers or regressors can lead to equal or better results than the average of all the individual models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It can also be proved that if the optimal weighting scheme is used, then a weighted averaging approach can outperform any of the individual classifiers or regressors that make up the ensemble or as good as the best performer at least.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] While the number of component classifiers of an ensemble has a great impact on the accuracy of prediction, there is a limited number of studies addressing this problem.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] *A priori* determining of ensemble size and the volume and velocity of big data streams make this even more crucial for online ensemble classifiers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Mostly statistical tests were used for determining the proper number of components.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] More recently, a theoretical framework suggested that there is an ideal number of component classifiers for an ensemble such that having more or less than this number of classifiers would deteriorate the accuracy.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It is called "the law of diminishing returns in ensemble construction." Their theoretical framework shows that using the same number of independent component classifiers as class labels gives the highest accuracy.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The Bayes optimal classifier is a classification technique.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It is an ensemble of all the hypotheses in the hypothesis space.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] On average, no other ensemble can outperform it.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The Naive Bayes classifier is a version of this that assumes that the data is conditionally independent on the class and makes the computation more feasible.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Each hypothesis is given a vote proportional to the likelihood that the training dataset would be sampled from a system if that hypothesis were true.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] To facilitate training data of finite size, the vote of each hypothesis is also multiplied by the prior probability of that hypothesis.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] where y is the predicted class, C is the set of all possible classes, H is the hypothesis space, P refers to a *probability*, and T is the training data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] As an ensemble, the Bayes optimal classifier represents a hypothesis that is not necessarily in H .
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The hypothesis represented by the Bayes optimal classifier, however, is the optimal hypothesis in *ensemble space* (the space of all possible ensembles consisting only of hypotheses in H ).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Bootstrap aggregation (*bagging*) involves training an ensemble on *bootstrapped* data sets.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] A bootstrapped set is created by selecting from original training data set with replacement.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Thus, a bootstrap set may contain a given example zero, one, or multiple times.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble members can also have limits on the features (e.g., nodes of a decision tree), to encourage exploring of diverse features.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The variance of local information in the bootstrap sets and feature considerations promote diversity in the ensemble, and can strengthen the ensemble.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] To reduce overfitting, a member can be validated using the out-of-bag set (the examples that are not in its bootstrap set).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Inference is done by **voting** of predictions of ensemble members, called **aggregation**.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It is illustrated below with an ensemble of four decision trees.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The query example is classified by each tree.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Because three of the four predict the *positive* class, the ensemble's overall classification is *positive*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Random forests like the one shown are a common application of bagging.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Boosting involves training successive models by emphasizing training data mis-classified by previously learned models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Initially, all data (D1) has equal weight and is used to learn a base model M1.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The examples mis-classified by M1 are assigned a weight greater than correctly classified examples.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] This boosted data (D2) is used to train a second base model M2, and so on.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] In some cases, boosting has yielded better accuracy than bagging, but tends to over-fit more.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The most common implementation of boosting is Adaboost, but some newer algorithms are reported to achieve better results.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Bayesian model averaging (BMA) makes predictions by averaging the predictions of models weighted by their posterior probabilities given the data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] BMA is known to generally give better answers than a single model, obtained, e.g., via stepwise regression, especially where very different models have nearly identical performance in the training set but may otherwise perform quite differently.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The question with any use of Bayes' theorem is the prior, i.e., the probability (perhaps subjective) that each model is the best to use for a given purpose.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Conceptually, BMA can be used with any prior.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] *R* packages ensembleBMA and BMA use the prior implied by the Bayesian information criterion, (BIC), following Raftery (1995).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] *R* package BAS supports the use of the priors implied by Akaike information criterion (AIC) and other criteria over the alternative models as well as priors over the coefficients.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The difference between BIC and AIC is the strength of preference for parsimony.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] BIC's penalty for model complexity is $\ln(n)k$ , while AIC's is $2k$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] On the other hand, AIC and AICc are asymptotically "efficient" (i.e., minimum mean square prediction error), while BIC is not .
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] (1994) showed that when BMA is used for classification, its expected error is at most twice the expected error of the Bayes optimal classifier.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Burnham and Anderson (1998, 2002) contributed greatly to introducing a wider audience to the basic ideas of Bayesian model averaging and popularizing the methodology.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The availability of software, including other free open-source packages for R beyond those mentioned above, helped make the methods accessible to a wider audience.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Bayesian model combination (BMC) is an algorithmic correction to Bayesian model averaging (BMA).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Instead of sampling each model in the ensemble individually, it samples from the space of possible ensembles (with model weights drawn randomly from a Dirichlet distribution having uniform parameters).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] This modification overcomes the tendency of BMA to converge toward giving all the weight to a single model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Although BMC is somewhat more computationally expensive than BMA, it tends to yield dramatically better results.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] BMC has been shown to be better on average (with statistical significance) than BMA and bagging.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Use of Bayes' law to compute model weights requires computing the probability of the data given each model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Typically, none of the models in the ensemble are exactly the distribution from which the training data were generated, so all of them correctly receive a value close to zero for this term.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] This would work well if the ensemble were big enough to sample the entire model-space, but this is rarely possible.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Consequently, each pattern in the training data will cause the ensemble weight to shift toward the model in the ensemble that is closest to the distribution of the training data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It essentially reduces to an unnecessarily complex method for doing model selection.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The possible weightings for an ensemble can be visualized as lying on a simplex.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] At each vertex of the simplex, all of the weight is given to a single model in the ensemble.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] BMA converges toward the vertex that is closest to the distribution of the training data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] By contrast, BMC converges toward the point where this distribution projects onto the simplex.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] In other words, instead of selecting the one model that is closest to the generating distribution, it seeks the combination of models that is closest to the generating distribution.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The results from BMA can often be approximated by using cross-validation to select the best model from a bucket of models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Likewise, the results from BMC may be approximated by using cross-validation to select the best ensemble combination from a random sampling of possible weightings.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] A "bucket of models" is an ensemble technique in which a model selection algorithm is used to choose the best model for each problem.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] When tested with only one problem, a bucket of models can produce no better results than the best model in the set, but when evaluated across many problems, it will typically produce much better results, on average, than any model in the set.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The most common approach used for model-selection is cross-validation selection (sometimes called a "bake-off contest").
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Cross-Validation Selection can be summed up as: "try them all with the training set, and pick the one that works best".
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Gating is a generalization of Cross-Validation Selection.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It involves training another learning model to decide which of the models in the bucket is best-suited to solve the problem.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Often, a perceptron is used for the gating model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It can be used to pick the "best" model, or it can be used to give a linear weight to the predictions from each model in the bucket.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] When a bucket of models is used with a large set of problems, it may be desirable to avoid training some of the models that take a long time to train.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Landmark learning is a meta-learning approach that seeks to solve this problem.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It involves training only the fast (but imprecise) algorithms in the bucket, and then using the performance of these algorithms to help determine which slow (but accurate) algorithm is most likely to do best.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The most common approach for training classifier is using Cross-entropy cost function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] However, one would like to train an ensemble of models that have diversity so when we combine them it would provide best results.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Assuming we use a simple ensemble of averaging K classifiers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] where $e^{k}$ is the cost function of the $k^{th}$ classifier, $q^{k}$ is the probability of the $k^{th}$ classifier, p is the true probability that we need to estimate and $\lambda$ is a parameter between 0 and 1 that define the diversity that we would like to establish.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] When $\lambda =0$ we want each classifier to do its best regardless of the ensemble and when $\lambda =1$ we would like the classifier to be as diverse as possible.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Stacking (sometimes called *stacked generalization*) involves training a model to combine the predictions of several other learning algorithms.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] If an arbitrary combiner algorithm is used, then stacking can theoretically represent any of the ensemble techniques described in this article, although, in practice, a logistic regression model is often used as the combiner.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Stacking typically yields performance better than any single one of the trained models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It has been successfully used on both supervised learning tasks (regression, classification and distance learning ) and unsupervised learning (density estimation).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It has also been used to estimate bagging's error rate.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It has been reported to out-perform Bayesian model-averaging.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The two top-performers in the Netflix competition utilized blending, which may be considered a form of stacking.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Bayesian predictive stacking generalizes the idea of stacking from the statistical estimation literature to the combination of posterior predictive distributions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] These ideas have also been developed and investigated for Gaussian process models, especially for spatial data analysis and can be used to construct transfer learning frameworks for massive spatial data sets.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Weighted majority algorithm (machine learning).
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] In recent years, due to growing computational power, which allows for training in large ensemble learning in a reasonable time frame, the number of ensemble learning applications has grown increasingly.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Land cover mapping is one of the major applications of Earth observation satellite sensors, using remote sensing and geospatial data, to identify the materials and objects which are located on the surface of target areas.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Generally, the classes of target materials include roads, buildings, rivers, lakes, and vegetation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Some different ensemble learning approaches based on artificial neural networks, kernel principal component analysis (KPCA), decision trees with boosting, random forest and automatic design of multiple classifier systems, are proposed to efficiently identify land cover objects.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Change detection is an image analysis problem, consisting of the identification of places where the land cover has changed over time.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Change detection is widely used in fields such as urban growth, forest and vegetation dynamics, land use and disaster monitoring.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The earliest applications of ensemble classifiers in change detection are designed with the majority voting, Bayesian model averaging, and the maximum posterior probability.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Given the growth of satellite data over time, the past decade sees more use of time series methods for continuous change detection from image stacks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] One example is a Bayesian ensemble changepoint detection method called BEAST, with the software available as a package Rbeast in R, Python, and Matlab.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Distributed denial of service is one of the most threatening cyber-attacks that may happen to an internet service provider.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] By combining the output of single classifiers, ensemble classifiers reduce the total error of detecting and discriminating such attacks from legitimate flash crowds.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Classification of malware codes such as computer viruses, computer worms, trojans, ransomware and spywares with the usage of machine learning techniques, is inspired by the document categorization problem.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning systems have shown a proper efficacy in this area.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Malware detection models, like all machine learning models, are vulnerable to adversarial machine learning attacks where an attacker pushes the boundary of what is classified as malware.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] By rotating through an ensemble of models using moving target defense, the attacker has a diminished knowledge advantage.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] An intrusion detection system monitors computer network or computer systems to identify intruder codes like an anomaly detection process.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning successfully aids such monitoring systems to reduce their total error.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Face recognition, which recently has become one of the most popular research areas of pattern recognition, copes with identification or verification of a person by their digital images.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Hierarchical ensembles based on Gabor Fisher classifier and independent component analysis preprocessing techniques are some of the earliest ensembles employed in this field.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] It is also being successfully used in facial emotion recognition.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Fraud detection deals with the identification of bank fraud, such as money laundering, credit card fraud and telecommunication fraud, which have vast domains of research and applications of machine learning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Because ensemble learning improves the robustness of the normal behavior modelling, it has been proposed as an efficient technique to detect such fraudulent cases and activities in banking and credit card systems.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning methods have been widely adopted in finance for tasks such as credit scoring, bankruptcy prediction, and risk management.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] By combining multiple base models, ensembles can exploit nonlinear relationships, handle high-dimensional and noisy data, and often deliver more stable out-of-sample performance than single models or traditional statistical baselines such as logistic regression and linear factor models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] This approach aligns with the broader trend in financial machine learning described by Marcos López de Prado, who argues that combining diverse learners can improve robustness, mitigate overfitting, and extract persistent patterns from noisy financial time series.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] In retail and corporate credit scoring, ensemble classifiers such as random forests, gradient boosting machines and stacked models are frequently used to assess default risk.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble methods have also been applied to corporate failure and bankruptcy prediction.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Studies comparing different ensemble constructions (such as bagging, boosting and heterogeneous classifier pools) report that well-tuned ensembles tend to achieve higher classification accuracy and more robust performance across industries than individual models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] The accuracy of prediction of business failure is a very crucial issue in financial decision-making.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Therefore, different ensemble classifiers are proposed to predict financial crises and financial distress.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Also, in the trade-based manipulation problem, where traders attempt to manipulate stock prices by buying and selling activities, ensemble classifiers are required to analyze the changes in the stock market data and detect suspicious symptom of stock price manipulation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Implementation of ensemble learning not only with machine learning models but also with mathematical frameworks such as hidden Markov models for applications in trading, regime detection, and asset pricing remains a rapidly developing area of research.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Ensemble classifiers have been successfully applied in neuroscience, proteomics and medical diagnosis like in neuro-cognitive disorder (i.e.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Alzheimer or myotonic dystrophy) detection based on MRI datasets, cervical cytology classification.
[src:mixture-of-experts/ensemble-learning] Besides, ensembles have been successfully applied in medical segmentation tasks, for example brain tumor and hyperintensities segmentation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:mixture-of-experts/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Both the experts and the weighting function are trained by minimizing some loss function, generally via gradient descent.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] There is much freedom in choosing the precise form of experts, the weighting function, and the loss function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The meta-pi network, reported by Hampshire and Waibel, uses $f(x)=\sum _{i}w(x)_{i}f_{i}(x)$ as the output.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The model is trained by performing gradient descent on the mean-squared error loss $L:={\frac {1}{N}}\sum _{k}\|y_{k}-f(x_{k})\|^{2}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In their original publication, they were solving the problem of classifying phonemes in speech signal from 6 different Japanese speakers, 2 females and 4 males.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They trained 6 experts, each being a "time-delayed neural network" (essentially a multilayered convolution network over the mel spectrogram).
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They found that the resulting mixture of experts dedicated 5 experts for 5 of the speakers, but the 6th (male) speaker does not have a dedicated expert, instead his voice was classified by a linear combination of the experts for the other 3 male speakers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The adaptive mixtures of local experts uses a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Each expert simply predicts a Gaussian distribution, and totally ignores the input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Specifically, the i -th expert predicts that the output is $y\sim N(\mu _{i},I)$ , where $\mu _{i}$ is a learnable parameter.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] For each input-output pair $(x,y)$ , the weighting function is changed to increase the weight on all experts that performed above average, and decrease the weight on all experts that performed below average.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This encourages the weighting function to learn to select only the experts that make the right predictions for each input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The i -th expert is changed to make its prediction closer to y , but the amount of change is proportional to $w(x)_{i}N(y|\mu _{i},I)$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Given input x , the prior probability that expert i is the right one is $w(x)_{i}$ , and $N(y|\mu _{i},I)$ is the likelihood of evidence y .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] So, ${\frac {w(x)_{i}N(y|\mu _{i},I)}{\sum _{j}w(x)_{j}N(y|\mu _{j},I)}}$ is the posterior probability for expert i , and so the rate of change for the i -th expert is proportional to its posterior probability.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In words, the experts that, in hindsight, seemed like the good experts to consult, are asked to learn on the example.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The experts that, in hindsight, were not, are left alone.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The combined effect is that the experts become specialized: Suppose two experts are both good at predicting a certain kind of input, but one is slightly better, then the weighting function would eventually learn to favor the better one.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] After that happens, the lesser expert is unable to obtain a high gradient signal, and becomes even worse at predicting such kind of input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Conversely, the lesser expert can become better at predicting other kinds of input, and increasingly pulled away into another region.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This has a positive feedback effect, causing each expert to move apart from the rest and take care of a local region alone (thus the name "*local* experts").
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Hierarchical mixtures of experts uses multiple levels of gating in a tree.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Each gating is a probability distribution over the next level of gatings, and the experts are on the leaf nodes of the tree.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] For example, a 2-level hierarchical MoE would have a first order gating function $w_{i}$ , and second order gating functions $w_{j|i}$ and experts $f_{j|i}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The mixture of experts, being similar to the gaussian mixture model, can also be trained by the expectation-maximization algorithm, just like gaussian mixture models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Specifically, during the expectation step, the "burden" for explaining each data point is assigned over the experts, and during the maximization step, the experts are trained to improve the explanations they got a high burden for, while the gate is trained to improve its burden assignment.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This can converge faster than gradient ascent on the log-likelihood.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The choice of gating function is often softmax.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Other than that, gating may use gaussian distributions and exponential families.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Instead of performing a weighted sum of all the experts, in hard MoE, only the highest ranked expert is chosen.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This can accelerate training and inference time.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The experts can use more general forms of multivariant gaussian distributions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In words, each expert learns to do linear regression, with a learnable uncertainty estimate.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] One can use different experts than gaussian distributions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] For example, one can use Laplace distribution, or Student's t-distribution.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This is later generalized for multi-class classification, with multinomial logistic regression experts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] One paper proposed mixture of softmaxes for autoregressive language modelling.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Specifically, consider a language model that given a previous text c , predicts the next word x .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The network encodes the text into a vector $v_{c}$ , and predicts the probability distribution of the next word as $\mathrm {Softmax} (v_{c}W)$ for an embedding matrix W .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The original paper demonstrated its effectiveness for recurrent neural networks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This was later found to work for Transformers as well.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The previous section described MoE as it was used before the era of deep learning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] After deep learning, MoE found applications in running the largest models, as a simple way to perform *conditional computation*: only parts of the model are used, the parts chosen according to what the input is.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The earliest paper that applies MoE to deep learning dates back to 2013, which proposed to use a different gating network at each layer in a deep neural network.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Specifically, each gating is a linear-ReLU-linear-softmax network, and each expert is a linear-ReLU network.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Since the output from the gating is not sparse, all expert outputs are needed, and no conditional computation is performed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The key goal when using MoE in deep learning is to reduce computing cost.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Consequently, for each query, only a small subset of the experts should be queried.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This makes MoE in deep learning different from classical MoE.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In classical MoE, the output for each query is a weighted sum of *all* experts' outputs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In deep learning MoE, the output for each query can only involve a few experts' outputs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Consequently, the key design choice in MoE becomes routing: given a batch of queries, how to route the queries to the best experts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The sparsely-gated MoE layer, published by researchers from Google Brain, uses feedforward networks as experts, and linear-softmax gating.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Similar to the previously proposed hard MoE, they achieve sparsity by a weighted sum of only the top-k experts, instead of the weighted sum of all of them.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Specifically, in a MoE layer, there are feedforward networks $f_{1},...,f_{n}$ , and a gating network w .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The gating network is defined by $w(x)=\mathrm {softmax} (\mathrm {top} _{k}(Wx+{\text{noise}}))$ , where $\mathrm {top} _{k}$ is a function that keeps the top-k entries of a vector the same, but sets all other entries to $-\infty$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The addition of noise helps with load balancing.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The choice of k is a hyperparameter that is chosen according to application.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The $k=1$ version is also called the Switch Transformer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The original Switch Transformer was applied to a T5 language model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] As demonstration, they trained a series of models for machine translation with alternating layers of MoE and LSTM, and compared with deep LSTM models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Table 3 shows that the MoE models used less inference time compute, despite having 30x more parameters.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This architectural module was published in 2017-01, within a few months of the publication of the Transformer architecture (2017-06-12), and they were combined into a multimodal architecture called MultiModel published 4 days later (2017-06-16).
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Vanilla MoE tend to have issues of load balancing: some experts are consulted often, while other experts rarely or not at all.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] To encourage the gate to select each expert with equal frequency (proper load balancing) within each batch, each MoE layer has two auxiliary loss functions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This is improved by Switch Transformer into a single auxiliary loss function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This loss is minimized at 1 , precisely when every expert has equal weight $1/n$ in all situations.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Researchers at DeepSeek designed a variant of MoE, with "shared experts" that are always queried, and "routed experts" that might not be.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They found that standard load balancing encourages the experts to be equally consulted, but this then causes experts to replicate the same core capacity, such as English grammar.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They proposed the shared experts to learn core capacities that are often used, and let the routed experts to learn the peripheral capacities that are rarely used.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They also proposed "auxiliary-loss-free load balancing strategy", which does not use auxiliary loss.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Instead, each expert i has an extra "expert bias" $b_{i}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] If an expert is being neglected, then their bias increases, and vice versa.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] During token assignment, each token picks the top-k experts, but with the bias added in.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] That is: $f(x)=\sum _{i{\text{ is in the top-k of }}\{w(x)_{j}+b_{j}\}_{j}}w(x)_{i}f_{i}(x)$ Note that the expert bias matters for picking the experts, but not in adding up the responses from the experts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] For a given batch of queries $\{x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{T}\}$ , each query is routed to one or more experts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] For example, if each query is routed to one expert as in Switch Transformers, and if the experts are load-balanced, then each expert should expect on average $T/n$ queries in a batch.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In practice, the experts cannot expect perfect load balancing: in some batches, one expert might be underworked, while in other batches, it would be overworked.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Since the inputs cannot move through the layer until every expert in the layer has finished the queries it is assigned, load balancing is important.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The capacity factor is sometimes used to enforce a hard constraint on load balancing.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Each expert is only allowed to process up to $c\cdot T/n$ queries in a batch.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The ST-MoE report found $c\in [1.25,2]$ to work well in practice.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In the original sparsely-gated MoE, only the top-k experts are queried, and their outputs are weighted-summed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Generally speaking, routing is an assignment problem: How to assign tokens to experts, such that a variety of constraints are followed (such as throughput, load balancing, etc.)?
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] There are typically three classes of routing algorithm: the experts choose the tokens ("expert choice"), the tokens choose the experts (the original sparsely-gated MoE), and a global assigner matching experts and tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] During inference, the MoE works over a large batch of tokens at any time.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] If the tokens were to choose the experts, then some experts might get few tokens, while a few experts get so many tokens that it exceeds their maximum batch size, so they would have to ignore some of the tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Similarly, if the experts were to choose the tokens, then some tokens might not be picked by any expert.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Dropping a token is not necessarily a serious problem, since in Transformers, due to residual connections, if a token is "dropped", it does not disappear.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Instead, its vector representation simply passes through the feedforward layer without change.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Other approaches include solving it as a constrained linear programming problem, using reinforcement learning to train the routing algorithm (since picking an expert is a discrete action, like in RL).
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The token-expert match may involve no learning ("static routing"): It can be done by a deterministic hash function or a random number generator.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] MoE layers are used in the largest transformer models, for which learning and inferring over the full model is too costly.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They are typically sparsely-gated, with sparsity 1 or 2.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In Transformer models, the MoE layers are often used to select the feedforward layers (typically a linear-ReLU-linear network), appearing in each Transformer block after the multiheaded attention.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This is because the feedforward layers take up an increasing portion of the computing cost as models grow larger.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] For example, in the Palm-540B model, 90% of parameters are in its feedforward layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] A trained Transformer can be converted to a MoE by duplicating its feedforward layers, with randomly initialized gating, then trained further.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] This is a technique called "sparse upcycling".
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] There are a large number of design choices involved in Transformer MoE that affect the training stability and final performance.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The OLMoE report describes these in some detail.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] As of 2023, models large enough to use MoE tend to be large language models, where each expert has on the order of 10 billion parameters.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Other than language models, Vision MoE is a Transformer model with MoE layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They demonstrated it by training a model with 15 billion parameters.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] MoE Transformer has also been applied for diffusion models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] A series of large language models from Google used MoE.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] GShard uses MoE with up to top-2 experts per layer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Specifically, the top-1 expert is always selected, and the top-2th expert is selected with probability proportional to that experts' weight according to the gating function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Later, GLaM demonstrated a language model with 1.2 trillion parameters, each MoE layer using top-2 out of 64 experts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Switch Transformers use top-1 in all MoE layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] The NLLB-200 by Meta AI is a machine translation model for 200 languages.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] Each MoE layer uses a hierarchical MoE with two levels.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] On the first level, the gating function chooses to use either a "shared" feedforward layer, or to use the experts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] If using the experts, then another gating function computes the weights and chooses the top-2 experts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] MoE large language models can be adapted for downstream tasks by instruction tuning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In December 2023, Mistral AI released Mixtral 8x7B under Apache 2.0 license.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] It is a MoE language model with 46.7B parameters, 8 experts, and sparsity 2.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] They also released a version finetuned for instruction following.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] In March 2024, Databricks released DBRX.
[src:mixture-of-experts/mixture-of-experts] It is a MoE language model with 132B parameters, 16 experts, and sparsity 4.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The **softmax function,** also known as **softargmax** or **normalized exponential function**, converts a tuple of K real numbers into a probability distribution over K possible outcomes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] It is a generalization of the logistic function to multiple dimensions, and is used in multinomial logistic regression.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The softmax function is often used as the last activation function of a neural network to normalize the output of a network to a probability distribution over predicted output classes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The softmax function takes as input a tuple z of K real numbers, and normalizes it into a probability distribution consisting of K probabilities proportional to the exponentials of the input numbers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] That is, prior to applying softmax, some tuple components could be negative, or greater than one; and might not sum to 1; but after applying softmax, each component will be in the interval $(0,1)$ , and the components will add up to 1, so that they can be interpreted as probabilities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Furthermore, the larger input components will correspond to larger probabilities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In words, the softmax applies the standard exponential function to each element $z_{i}$ of the input tuple $\mathbf {z}$ (consisting of K real numbers), and normalizes these values by dividing by the sum of all these exponentials.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The normalization ensures that the sum of the components of the output vector $\sigma (\mathbf {z} )$ is 1.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The term "softmax" derives from the amplifying effects of the exponential on any maxima in the input tuple.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] For example, the standard softmax of $(1,2,8)$ is approximately $(0.001,0.002,0.997)$ , which amounts to assigning almost all of the total unit weight in the result to the position of the tuple's maximal element (of 8).
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In general, instead of e a different base b > 0 can be used.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] As above, if b > 1 then larger input components will result in larger output probabilities, and increasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the largest input values.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Conversely, if 0 < b < 1 then smaller input components will result in larger output probabilities, and decreasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the smallest input values.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] A value proportional to the reciprocal of β is sometimes referred to as the *temperature*: ${\textstyle \beta =1/kT}$ , where k is typically 1 or the Boltzmann constant and T is the temperature.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] A higher temperature results in a more uniform output distribution (i.e. with higher entropy; it is "more random"), while a lower temperature results in a sharper output distribution, with one value dominating.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In some fields, the base is fixed, corresponding to a fixed scale, while in others the parameter β (or T) is varied.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The softmax function is a multiple-variable generalization of the logistic function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The Softmax function is a smooth approximation to the arg max function: the function whose value is the *index* of a tuple's largest element.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Softmax is not a smooth maximum (that is, a smooth approximation to the maximum function).
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The term "softmax" is also used for the closely related LogSumExp function, which is a smooth maximum.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] For this reason, some prefer the more accurate term "softargmax", though the term "softmax" is conventional in machine learning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] This section uses the term "softargmax" for clarity.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] For example, in this encoding $\operatorname {arg\,max} (1,5,10)=(0,0,1),$ since the third argument is the maximum.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] This can be generalized to multiple arg max values (multiple equal $z_{i}$ being the maximum) by dividing the 1 between all max args; formally 1/k where k is the number of arguments assuming the maximum.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] With the last expression given in the introduction, softargmax is now a smooth approximation of arg max: as ⁠ $\beta \to \infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg max.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In fact, softargmax is continuous, but arg max is not continuous at the singular set where two coordinates are equal, while the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The reason it fails to converge uniformly is that for inputs where two coordinates are almost equal (and one is the maximum), the arg max is the index of one or the other, so a small change in input yields a large change in output.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] However, softargmax does converge compactly on the non-singular set.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Conversely, as ⁠ $\beta \to -\infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg min in the same way, where here the singular set is points with two arg *min* values.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] It is also the case that, for any fixed β, if one input ⁠ $z_{i}$ ⁠ is much larger than the others *relative* to the temperature, $T=1/\beta$ , the output is approximately the arg max.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The softmax function is used in various multiclass classification methods, such as multinomial logistic regression (also known as softmax regression), multiclass linear discriminant analysis, naive Bayes classifiers, and artificial neural networks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The operation is equivalent to applying a linear operator defined by $\mathbf {w}$ to tuples $\mathbf {x}$ , thus transforming the original, probably highly-dimensional, input to vectors in a K-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{K}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The standard softmax function is often used in the final layer of a neural network-based classifier.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Such networks are commonly trained under a log loss (or cross-entropy) regime, giving a non-linear variant of multinomial logistic regression.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Here, the Kronecker delta is used for simplicity (cf. the derivative of a sigmoid function, being expressed via the function itself).
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] To ensure stable numerical computations subtracting the maximum value from the input tuple is common.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] This approach, while not altering the output or the derivative theoretically, enhances stability by directly controlling the maximum exponent value computed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] If the function is scaled with the parameter $\beta$ , then these expressions must be multiplied by $\beta$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] See multinomial logit for a probability model which uses the softmax activation function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In the field of reinforcement learning, a softmax function can be used to convert values into action probabilities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] where the action value $q_{t}(a)$ corresponds to the expected reward of following action a and $\tau$ is called a temperature parameter (in allusion to statistical mechanics).
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] For high temperatures ( $\tau \to \infty$ ), all actions have nearly the same probability and the lower the temperature, the more expected rewards affect the probability.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] For a low temperature ( $\tau \to 0^{+}$ ), the probability of the action with the highest expected reward tends to 1.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In neural network applications, the number K of possible outcomes is often large, e.g. in case of neural language models that predict the most likely outcome out of a vocabulary which might contain millions of possible words.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] This can make the calculations for the softmax layer (i.e. the matrix multiplications to determine the $z_{i}$ , followed by the application of the softmax function itself) computationally expensive.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] What's more, the gradient descent backpropagation method for training such a neural network involves calculating the softmax for every training example, and the number of training examples can also become large.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The computational effort for the softmax became a major limiting factor in the development of larger neural language models, motivating various remedies to reduce training times.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Approaches that reorganize the softmax layer for more efficient calculation include the **hierarchical softmax** and the **differentiated softmax**.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The hierarchical softmax (introduced by Morin and Bengio in 2005) uses a binary tree structure where the outcomes (vocabulary words) are the leaves and the intermediate nodes are suitably selected "classes" of outcomes, forming latent variables.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The desired probability (softmax value) of a leaf (outcome) can then be calculated as the product of the probabilities of all nodes on the path from the root to that leaf.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Ideally, when the tree is balanced, this would reduce the computational complexity from $O(K)$ to $O(\log _{2}K)$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In practice, results depend on choosing a good strategy for clustering the outcomes into classes.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] A Huffman tree was used for this in Google's word2vec models (introduced in 2013) to achieve scalability.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] A second kind of remedies is based on approximating the softmax (during training) with modified loss functions that avoid the calculation of the full normalization factor.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] These include methods that restrict the normalization sum to a sample of outcomes (e.g.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The standard softmax is numerically unstable because of large exponentiations.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Subtracting by it guarantees that the exponentiations result in at most 1, see translation invariance in the mathematical properties.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] It can be efficiently computed on a GPU cluster using the FlashAttention algorithm.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Along the main diagonal $(x,\,x,\,\dots ,\,x),$ softmax is just the uniform distribution on outputs, $(1/n,\dots ,1/n)$ : equal scores yield equal probabilities.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Geometrically, softmax is constant along diagonals: this is the dimension that is eliminated, and corresponds to the softmax output being independent of a translation in the input scores (a choice of 0 score).
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] By contrast, softmax is not invariant under scaling.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The standard logistic function is the special case for a 1-dimensional axis in 2-dimensional space, say the *x*-axis in the (x, y) plane.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The softmax function was used in statistical mechanics as the Boltzmann distribution in the foundational paper Boltzmann (1868), formalized and popularized in the influential textbook Gibbs (1902).
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The use of the softmax in decision theory is credited to R.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Duncan Luce, who used the axiom of independence of irrelevant alternatives in rational choice theory to deduce the softmax in Luce's choice axiom for relative preferences.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] In machine learning, the term "softmax" is credited to John S.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The output has most of its weight where the "4" was in the original input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] This is what the function is normally used for: to highlight the largest values and suppress values which are significantly below the maximum value.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] But note: a change of *temperature* changes the output.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] This shows that high temperatures de-emphasize the maximum value.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] The softmax function generates probability predictions densely distributed over its support.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Other functions like sparsemax or α-entmax can be used when sparse probability predictions are desired.
[src:mixture-of-experts/softmax-function] Also the Gumbel-softmax reparametrization trick can be used when sampling from a discrete-discrete distribution needs to be mimicked in a differentiable manner.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] In numerical analysis and scientific computing, a **sparse matrix** or **sparse array** is a matrix in which most of the elements are zero.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] There is no strict definition regarding the proportion of zero-value elements for a matrix to qualify as **sparse** but a common criterion is that the number of non-zero elements is roughly equal to the number of rows or columns.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if most of the elements are non-zero, the matrix is considered **dense**.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The number of zero-valued elements divided by the total number of elements (e.g., *m* × *n* for an *m* × *n* matrix) is sometimes referred to as the **sparsity** of the matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Conceptually, sparsity corresponds to systems with few pairwise interactions.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] For example, consider a line of balls connected by springs from one to the next: this is a sparse system, as only adjacent balls are coupled.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if the same line of balls were to have springs connecting each ball to all other balls, the system would correspond to a dense matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The concept of sparsity is useful in combinatorics and application areas such as network theory and numerical analysis, which typically have a low density of significant data or connections.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Large sparse matrices often appear in scientific or engineering applications when solving partial differential equations.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] When storing and manipulating sparse matrices on a computer, it is beneficial and often necessary to use specialized algorithms and data structures that take advantage of the sparse structure of the matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Specialized computers have been made for sparse matrices, as they are common in the machine learning field.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Operations using standard dense-matrix structures and algorithms are slow and inefficient when applied to large sparse matrices as processing and memory are wasted on the zeros.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Sparse data is by nature more easily compressed and thus requires significantly less storage.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Some very large sparse matrices are infeasible to manipulate using standard dense-matrix algorithms.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The band matrices form a special class of sparse matrix where the non-zero elements are concentrated near the main diagonal.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] A band matrix is characterised by its lower and upper bandwidths, which refer to the number of diagonals below and above (respectively) the main diagonal between which all of the non-zero entries are contained.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Formally, the lower bandwidth of a matrix **A** is the smallest number *p* such that the entry *a**i*,*j* vanishes whenever *i* > *j* + *p*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Similarly, the upper bandwidth is the smallest number *p* such that *a**i*,*j* = 0 whenever *i* < *j* − *p* (Golub & Van Loan 1996, §1.2.1).
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] For example, a tridiagonal matrix has lower bandwidth 1 and upper bandwidth 1.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] As another example, the following sparse matrix has lower and upper bandwidth both equal to 3.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Matrices with reasonably small upper and lower bandwidth are known as band matrices and often lend themselves to simpler algorithms than general sparse matrices; or one can sometimes apply dense matrix algorithms and gain efficiency simply by looping over a reduced number of indices.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] By rearranging the rows and columns of a matrix **A** it may be possible to obtain a matrix **A**′ with a lower bandwidth.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] A number of algorithms are designed for bandwidth minimization.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix is the extreme case of a band matrix, with zero upper and lower bandwidth.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix can be stored efficiently by storing just the entries in the main diagonal as a one-dimensional array, so a diagonal *n* × *n* matrix requires only *n* entries in memory.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] A symmetric sparse matrix arises as the adjacency matrix of an undirected graph; it can be stored efficiently as an adjacency list.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] A block-diagonal matrix consists of sub-matrices along its diagonal blocks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The *fill-in* of a matrix are those entries that change from an initial zero to a non-zero value during the execution of an algorithm.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] To reduce the memory requirements and the number of arithmetic operations used during an algorithm, it is useful to minimize the fill-in by switching rows and columns in the matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The symbolic Cholesky decomposition can be used to calculate the worst possible fill-in before doing the actual Cholesky decomposition.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] There are other methods than the Cholesky decomposition in use.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Orthogonalization methods (such as QR factorization) are common, for example, when solving problems by least squares methods.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] While the theoretical fill-in is still the same, in practical terms the "false non-zeros" can be different for different methods.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] And symbolic versions of those algorithms can be used in the same manner as the symbolic Cholesky to compute worst case fill-in.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Both iterative and direct methods exist for sparse matrix solving.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Iterative methods, such as conjugate gradient method and GMRES utilize fast computations of matrix-vector products $Ax_{i}$ , where matrix A is sparse.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The use of preconditioners can significantly accelerate convergence of such iterative methods.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] A matrix is typically stored as a two-dimensional array.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Each entry in the array represents an element *a**i*,*j* of the matrix and is accessed by the two indices *i* and *j*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Conventionally, *i* is the row index, numbered from top to bottom, and *j* is the column index, numbered from left to right.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] For an *m* × *n* matrix, the amount of memory required to store the matrix in this format is proportional to *m* × *n* (disregarding the fact that the dimensions of the matrix also need to be stored).
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] In the case of a sparse matrix, substantial memory requirement reductions can be realized by storing only the non-zero entries.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Depending on the number and distribution of the non-zero entries, different data structures can be used and yield huge savings in memory when compared to the basic approach.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The trade-off is that accessing the individual elements becomes more complex and additional structures are needed to be able to recover the original matrix unambiguously.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] DOK consists of a dictionary that maps (row, column)-pairs to the value of the elements.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Elements that are missing from the dictionary are taken to be zero.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The format is good for incrementally constructing a sparse matrix in random order, but poor for iterating over non-zero values in lexicographical order.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] One typically constructs a matrix in this format and then converts to another more efficient format for processing.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] LIL stores one list per row, with each entry containing the column index and the value.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Typically, these entries are kept sorted by column index for faster lookup.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] This is another format good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] COO stores a list of (row, column, value) tuples.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Ideally, the entries are sorted first by row index and then by column index, to improve random access times.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] This is another format that is good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The *compressed sparse row* (CSR) or *compressed row storage* (CRS) or Yale format represents a matrix **M** by three (one-dimensional) arrays, that respectively contain nonzero values, the extents of rows, and column indices.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] It is similar to COO, but compresses the row indices, hence the name.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] This format allows fast row access and matrix-vector multiplications (**M***x*).
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The CSR format has been in use since at least the mid-1960s, with the first complete description appearing in 1967.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The CSR format stores a sparse *m* × *n* matrix **M** in row form using three (one-dimensional) arrays (V, COL_INDEX, ROW_INDEX).
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Let NNZ denote the number of nonzero entries in **M**.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Then we take slices from V and COL_INDEX starting at row_start and ending at row_end.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] To extract the row 1 (the second row) of this matrix we set `row_start=1` and `row_end=2`.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] We now know that in row 1 we have one element at column 1 with value 8.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] In this case the CSR representation contains 13 entries, compared to 16 in the original matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The CSR format saves on memory only when NNZ < (*m* (*n* − 1) − 1) / 2.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The whole is stored as 21 entries: 8 in V, 8 in COL_INDEX, and 5 in ROW_INDEX.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Note that in this format, the first value of ROW_INDEX is always zero and the last is always NNZ, so they are in some sense redundant (although in programming languages where the array length needs to be explicitly stored, NNZ would not be redundant).
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Nonetheless, this does avoid the need to handle an exceptional case when computing the length of each row, as it guarantees the formula ROW_INDEX[*i* + 1] − ROW_INDEX[*i*] works for any row *i*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Moreover, the memory cost of this redundant storage is likely insignificant for a sufficiently large matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The (old and new) Yale sparse matrix formats are instances of the CSR scheme.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The old Yale format works exactly as described above, with three arrays; the new format combines ROW_INDEX and COL_INDEX into a single array and handles the diagonal of the matrix separately.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] For logical adjacency matrices, the data array can be omitted, as the existence of an entry in the row array is sufficient to model a binary adjacency relation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] It is likely known as the Yale format because it was proposed in the 1977 Yale Sparse Matrix Package report from Department of Computer Science at Yale University.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] CSC is similar to CSR except that values are read first by column, a row index is stored for each value, and column pointers are stored.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] For example, CSC is (val, row_ind, col_ptr), where val is an array of the (top-to-bottom, then left-to-right) non-zero values of the matrix; row_ind is the row indices corresponding to the values; and, col_ptr is the list of val indexes where each column starts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The name is based on the fact that column index information is compressed relative to the COO format.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] One typically uses another format (LIL, DOK, COO) for construction.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] This format is efficient for arithmetic operations, column slicing, and matrix-vector products.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] This is the traditional format for specifying a sparse matrix in MATLAB (via the `sparse` function).
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] Many software libraries support sparse matrices, and provide solvers for sparse matrix equations.
[src:mixture-of-experts/sparse-matrix] The term *sparse matrix* was possibly coined by Harry Markowitz who initiated some pioneering work but then left the field.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:mixture-of-experts/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
